codex
I have enough context to change the PoC now. The fix is to keep the successful access-control proof, but broaden the profit leg so it no longer assumes the bridge is pre-funded with a short hardcoded token list: first try real escrow drains across a wider set, then fall back to forged `finalizeERC20Withdrawal` minting against existing Optimism-mintable L1 tokens if the bridge has no escrowed balance at this fork block.

Plan:
1. Preserve stage ordering and the exact root cause: replay `initialize`, replace `messenger`, satisfy `onlyOtherBridge`, prove the ETH withdrawal bypass.
2. Expand the ERC20 profit stage into two branches:
   - Native-token escrow branch: drain any bridge-held L1 token from a broader candidate set.
   - Optimism-mintable branch: mint an already-deployed on-chain token via forged `finalizeERC20Withdrawal`, which uses the same forged-messenger causality but does not depend on pre-existing escrow.
3. Verify the file compiles locally and keep comments tight around why the mint fallback is still the same vulnerability class and why no extra funding route is required in this fork state.
